  .SH "NAME"
search \- find and list objects in a BRL\-CAD database


  
  .SH "SYNOPSIS"

    .HP \w'\fBsearch\fR\ 'u

      \fBsearch\fR
       [\fIoptions\fR...]
       [\fIpath1\fR]
       [\fIpath2\fR...]
       [\fIsearch\ plan\fR...]
    

  

  .SH "DESCRIPTION"


    .PP
\fBsearch\fR
works in a fashion similar to Unix\-style find commands (internally it is based on OpenBSD\*(Aqs and NetBSD\*(Aqs find code) but searches
\fIobjects\fR
in the current open database in MGED rather than files in a file system\&. One or more search paths are specified for searching, and a search plan specifies filters through which objects in the search paths are tested\&. The names of objects satisfying all of the filters are returned as the command output\&.


    .PP
Search Inputs are specified using
PATHS
and matching of objects is done according to a search plan built using boolean expressions constructed using the
PRIMITIVES
and
OPERATORS
described below\&. Note that
OPTIONS
are not used to form search plans \- unlike the search plan they are specified
\fIbefore\fR
the paths and are used to control settings that apply globally to
\fBsearch\fR\*(Aqs behavior and reporting during the execution of the search\&.


    .PP
The results of the search command will be sorted according to David Koelle\*(Aqs "alphanum" algorithm, which is basically a human\-intuitive ordering for strings with letters and numbers\&. For example, a result returning d1\&.r, d10\&.r and d2\&.r will be sorted as:
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
d1\&.r
d2\&.r
d10\&.r
      
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp
instead of the default ASCII character ordering, which would look like:
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
d1\&.r
d10\&.r
d2\&.r
      
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp


  

  .SH "OPTIONS"


    

      .PP
\fB\-a\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  Overrides the hidden flag when assembling path lists, if a generic toplevel path has been specified\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-Q\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  Exit quietly without printing error messages if the search plan contains errors\&. Primarily used in situations where programs automatically generate search invocations\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-v[v\&.\&.]\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  Prints extra (verbose) information in results\&. Can be stacked up to 3 times for increasingly verbose printing\&. (See
Example 22
for in\-depth usage)

	
      .RE
    

  

  .SH "PATHS:"

    .PP
By default, only the "top level" objects in any search are used as starting points in the search\&. The default mode if no path is explicitly specified returns a list of all objects found matching the criteria using the top level objects as inputs\&. Specifying paths is done as follows:


    .PP
.it 1 an-trap
.nr an-no-space-flag 1
.nr an-break-flag 1
.br
.B Table\ \&1.\ \&Path Specifiers
.TS
allbox tab(:);
lB lB.
T{
Form
T}:T{
Results
T}
.T&
c l
c l
c l
c l
c l
c l
c l
c l
c l.
T{
/
T}:T{
Search using top level objects in database as starting points, return list of matching full paths\&.
T}
T{
\&.
T}:T{
Search using top level objects in database as starting points, return list of all matching objects (defualt)\&.
T}
T{
|
T}:T{
Iterate over all objects in the database without doing a tree walk, return list of all matching objects\&.
T}
T{
|/
T}:T{
Search using every object in the database as a starting point, return list of matching full paths\&.
T}
T{
|\&.
T}:T{
Search using every object in the database as a starting point, return list of all matching objects\&.
T}
T{
/objname
T}:T{
Use object \fIobjname\fR as the starting point, return list of matching full paths\&.
T}
T{
objname
T}:T{
Use object \fIobjname\fR as the starting point, return list of all matching objects\&.
T}
T{
|/objname
T}:T{
Use every object below \fIobjname\fR as starting points, return list of matching full paths\&.
T}
T{
|objname
T}:T{
Use every object below \fIobjname\fR as starting points, return list of all matching objects\&.
T}
.TE
.sp 1
One search command may use multiple paths, each of which can specify its own mode \- such a "mixed mode" search will return a list of full paths and objects in the order paths were supplied to search\&.

    .PP
The "flat" searches that are specified by using \*(Aq|\*(Aq as a modifier to other paths will use every object in the database as starting points for full tree walks and consequently will be significantly more expensive for complex tree hierarchies\&. The "truly flat" iterative search triggered by the the stand\-alone \*(Aq|\*(Aq path specifier will be faster, but because it does not walk the tree hierarchy depth\-related options (\-above, \-below, \-depth, etc\&.) will not function\&.


  

  .SH "PRIMITIVES:"


    

      .PP
\fB\-attr\fR \fIattrib[>/</=val]\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  Returns TRUE if the object has attribute
\fIattrib\fR\&. If a specific value is also supplied for the attribute with an equal condition, TRUE is returned if the object both has the attribute and the attribute is set to value
\fIval\&.\fR
In the case of >, <, >=, and <= there are two possibilities \- if
\fIval\fR
is numerical a numerical comparison is performed, otherwise a string comparison is performed\&. Both
\fIattrib\fR
and
\fIval\fR
are treated as patterns under shell pattern matching rules when a string comparison is performed, but in numerical mode only the attribute name is pattern matched\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-bool\fR \fIu/+/\-\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  True if the object in question is being combined into the local hierarchy with the specified boolean operation\&. Recognized types are Union (u), Intersection (+), and Subtraction (\-)\&.
.sp

	  Note that by convention, top level objects are implicitly "unioned" into the database\&. To see only objects that have been unioned into a comb tree without returning the top level comb object as well, use the
\fB\-mindepth\fR
option to filter for returns deeper in the tree\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-depth\fR \fI[>/</=]depth\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  True if the depth of the object in the tree is within the range specified\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-exec\fR \fIexpression arg1 arg2 \&.\&.\&. ";"\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  True if the Tcl expression returns true\&. Any pair of curly braces (\*(Aq{}\*(Aq) in an arguemt is replaced by the name or full path of the object\&. The semicolon terminates the argument list and must not be omitted\&. Remember to quote the parameters properly\&. The semicolon must stand on its own and must be quoted\&.
.sp

	  When using multiple \-exec filters, keep in mind that filters are evaluated lazily, so if you have two \-execs and the first one returns false for one node, the second one will not run at all\&.

	
      .RE

      .PP
\fB\-iname\fR \fIpattern\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  Like
\fBname\fR
except the match is case insensitive\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-iregex\fR \fIpattern\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  Like
\fBregex\fR
except the match is case insensitive\&.

	
      .RE

      .PP
\fB\-matrix\fR \fIIDN|{#,#,#,#,#,#,#,#,#,#,#,#,#,#,#,#}\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  True if the object in question is being combined into the local hierarchy with an with the specified matrix\&. This is useful in combination with the
\fB!\fR
operator, for finding objects in a hierarchy with matricies over them\&. "IDN" is a shorthand that allows users to specify an identity matrix more succinctly\&.

	
      .RE

      .PP
\fB\-maxdepth\fR \fIn\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  True if the depth of the object in the tree is less than or equal to
\fIn\fR\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-mindepth\fR \fIn\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  True if the depth of the object in the tree is greater than or equal to
\fIn\fR\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-name\fR \fIpattern\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  True if the object name (not the full path, just the name) matches
\fIpattern\fR\&. The evaluation is done according to shell pattern matching rules\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-nnodes\fR \fIn\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  True if the object is a combination and has
\fIn\fR
nodes\&. This option also supports supplying <, >, <=, and >= in front of the number to support returning true for objects with node counts less than, greater than, less than or equal to, and greater than or equal to
\fIn\fR\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-param\fR \fIparam[>/</=val]\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  Returns TRUE if the object has parameter
\fIparam\fR\&. Unlike
\fB\-attr\fR, which looks only at general attributes stored as metadata on objects, the
\fB\-param\fR
filters based only on the internal geometric object\*(Aqs characteristics\&. If a specific value is also supplied for the parameter with an equal condition, TRUE is returned if the object both has the parameter and the parameter is set to value
\fIval\&.\fR
In the case of >, <, >=, and <= there are two possibilities \- if
\fIval\fR
is numerical a numerical comparison is performed, otherwise a string comparison is performed\&. Both
\fIattrib\fR
and
\fIval\fR
are treated as patterns under shell pattern matching rules when a string comparison is performed, but in numerical mode only the parameter name is pattern matched\&.
.sp

	  The following table outlines what parameters are visible to the
\fB\-param\fR
option\&. Because BRL\-CAD uses the same internal containers for some types, some parameters will be present even when they do not make sense for the specific subtype\&. Examples include using arb8\*(Aqs container for arb4 and tgc for rcc\&. Note: there are also a number of primitives whose parameters are not exposed in a way that that
\fB\-param\fR
can access them: arbn, ars, brep, bspline, dsp, metaball, nmg, pipe, pnts, and poly\&.
.sp
.it 1 an-trap
.nr an-no-space-flag 1
.nr an-break-flag 1
.br
.B Table\ \&2.\ \&Primitive Parameters
.TS
allbox tab(:);
lB lB.
