.sp 1
.sp

	  
.sp

	  As a convenience, the
\fB\-type\fR
option will also recognize the pattern
\fBshape\fR, which will match any object that is
\fInot\fR
a combination, region, annotation, constraint, grip or joint\&.
.sp

	  In order to identify shapes defined as implicit solids using the "plate mode" methodology, the pattern
\fBplate\fR
will match any object whose internal definition indiciates it is of that type\&. Currently such objects are possible with "bot" and "brep" objects\&.
.sp

	  The the pattern
\fBvolume\fR
can be used as a mirror of plate, in that it will report objects that clearly define a non\-implicit solid volume\&. Its determination is local \- for example, combs aren\*(Aqt matched because a comb may be made up of non\-volumetric objects\&. In particular, plate mode objects will not match because their volume is implicit, and (for example) surface mode BoTs will not match because they don\*(Aqt define a volume\&.

	
      .RE
    

  

  .SH "OPERATORS"


    

      .PP
\fB(\fR \fIexpression\fR \fB)\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  Evaluates to true if the expression inside the parentheses evaluates to true\&. Used to establish order of operations\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-below[>/</=val]\fR \fIexpression\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  The below operator applies the expression to every object below the matching object in the tree hierarchy\&. E\&.g\&. searching with \-below \-name start\e* on /component/region\&.r/start_comb\&.c/prim1\&.s would return prim1\&.s, as the object below start_comb\&.c
.sp

	  Optionally, inequality and equality constraints on depth can be appended to the operator to limit what relative depths are accepted as matches\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fIexpression\fR \fB\-and\fR \fIexpression\fR (a\&.k\&.a\&. \-a)
.RS 4

	
	
	  The and operator operates like the logical AND operator \- TRUE only if both expressions are true\&. AND is the default operator assumed if two expressions are present with no operator explicitly defined\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-above[>/</=val]\fR \fIexpression\fR
.RS 4

	
	
	  The above operator applies the expression to every object above the current full path to that object, and returns TRUE if one or more of them satisfies the expression\&. E\&.g\&., searching with \-above \-name s\e* on /component/region\&.r/start_comb\&.c/prim1\&.s would return TRUE for /component and /component/region\&.r as start_comb\&.c is below both of them, but would return FALSE for any deeper objects (i\&.e\&., prim1\&.s in this example)\&.
.sp

	  Optionally, inequality and equality constraints on depth can be appended to the operator to limit what relative depths are accepted as matches\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fB\-not\fR \fIexpression\fR (a\&.k\&.a\&. !)
.RS 4

	
	
	  The logical NOT operator \- returns the opposite of the evaluation result of expression\&.

	
      .RE
      .PP
\fIexpression\fR \fB\-or\fR \fIexpression\fR (a\&.k\&.a\&. \-o)
.RS 4

	
	
	  The logical OR operator \- true if either expression is true\&.

	
      .RE
    
  

  .SH "A NOTE ON EXPRESSIONS"


    .PP
All primaries and operands must be expressed as separate arguments to search\&. In practice, this means that there must be a space between each element in a search expression\&. E\&.g\&. !(\-name [a\-z] \-or \-name [0\-9]) must be written as:


    .PP
! ( \-name [a\-z] \-or \-name [0\-9] )


    .PP
While this may seem like a rather verbose way of writing the expression, it greatly simplifies the parsing of the expression and is standard for virtually all
\fBfind\fR
type commands\&. Because [a\-z] and [0\-9] are atomic arguments as far as search is concerned, they should NOT be expanded in a similar fashion\&.

  

  .SH "A NOTE ON SPECIAL CHARACTERS"


    .PP
Depending upon your environment, special characters such as wildcards or brackets may require an escape character (\e)\&. Double quotes can also be used to surround the expression negating the need for multiple escape characters\&. The following three examples show a search for names containing the string "tire" using two wildcards\&.

	.PP
\fBsearch \-name *tire*\fR

	.PP
\fBsearch \-name \e*tire\e*\fR

	.PP
\fBsearch \-name "*tire*"\fR

	.PP
If an escape character is required but not used, an "unknown option passed to find_create" error will be displayed\&.


  	

  .SH "EXAMPLES"


    .PP
The following are run from the MGED command prompt:

    .PP
\fBExample\ \&1.\ \&Shell Globbing Based Pattern Match of Object Name\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch \-name *\&.s\fR

      .PP
Find all objects in the database with names ending in "\&.s"\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&2.\ \&Full Path Instance Reporting of Search Results\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch / \-name *\&.s\fR

      .PP
Find all instances of objects in the database with names ending in "\&.s"\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&3.\ \&Name Pattern Matching at Depth >= 3\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch / \-name *\&.s \-mindepth 3\fR

      .PP
Find all instances of objects in the database with names ending in "\&.s" that are 3 or more levels deep in their tree\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&4.\ \&Finding all Objects in a Subtree\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch group1 \-name *\&.r\fR

      .PP
Find all objects within group1 in the database that have names ending in "\&.r" Note that this will return a list of objects, not the full path information associated with each instance of the objects matched\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&5.\ \&Finding all Instances of Objects in a Subtree\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch /group1 \-name *\&.r\fR

      .PP
Find all instances of objects within group1 in the database that have names ending in "\&.r" Note that, unlike the previous example, this will return the full path information associated with each instance of the objects matched\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&6.\ \&Finding all Instances of a Sub\-Path\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch / \-path \e*r245\fR

      .PP
Find all paths which end with the object r245\&. Note that all paths generated by objects
\fIbelow\fR
r245 will not match this pattern\&. To find all paths with r245 in them, use the following pattern:

      .PP
\fBsearch / \-path \e*r245\e*\fR

      .PP
If you need to match an object path that is potentially ambiguous (say, r1 when there are lots of regions that match the r1* globbing rule) add the trailing slash to the expression:

      .PP
\fBsearch / \-path \e*r1\e/\e*\fR

    



    .PP
\fBExample\ \&7.\ \&Searching by Type\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch \&. \-type eto\fR

      .PP
Find all objects in the database that are elliptical tori\&. Note that a path of "\&." produces the same search behavior as the default behavior for an unspecified path\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&8.\ \&Finding all Instances of Nested Regions\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch / \-type region \-below \-type region\fR

      .PP
Find all instances of objects of type region that contain a region\&. This searches for regions being used within the subtrees of other regions, which is considered bad practice in BRL\-CAD\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&9.\ \&Finding all Assemblies\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch / \-type comb ! \-below \-type region ! \-type region\fR

      .PP
Find all instances of objects of type combination that are not below regions and are not themselves regions\&. These are regarded as "assemblies" in BRL\-CAD\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&10.\ \&Finding all Combinations below Regions\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch / \-type comb \-below \-type region ! \-type region\fR

      .PP
Find all instances of combinations that are not regions and do not contain regions\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&11.\ \&Finding all Empty Combinations\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch \-nnodes 0\fR

      .PP
Find all combinations containing zero nodes\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&12.\ \&Finding all Combinations With 10 or More Nodes\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch \-nnodes >=10\fR

      .PP
Find all combinations with 10 or more nodes\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&13.\ \&Finding all Intersected Objects\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch \-bool +\fR

      .PP
Find all objects that are combined into one or more trees using the Intersect boolean operation somewhere in the \&.g file\&. This approach only identifies which objects are intersected somewhere in the tree, not where specifically they are intersected\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&14.\ \&Finding all Instances of Object Intersection\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch / \-bool +\fR

      .PP
Find all boolean operations that use the Intersect boolean operation and report the full paths to those objects\&. This approach reports all individual cases where an object has been combined into a hierarchy by intersection, not just which objects have been included with the intersection operator\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&15.\ \&Finding all Unions Within a Comb\*(Aqs Tree\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch /all\&.g \-mindepth 1 \-bool u\fR

      .PP
Find all unions within the all\&.g tree hierarchy, excluding all\&.g itself\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&16.\ \&Finding all Non\-Subtracted Regions below Regions\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch / \-type region \-below \-type region ! \-bool \-\fR

      .PP
A more nuanced variation on finding nested regions that adds a check to make sure that the regions aren\*(Aqt being subtracted\&. While not ideal, using a subtraction does avoid the modeling error of two volumes claiming the three dimensional space and is arguably acceptable \- the below command finds nested region instances that are considered errors\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&17.\ \&Finding all Non\-Identity Matrix Instances\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch / ! \-matrix IDN \-\fR

      .PP
Reports all comb instances included in their parent comb with a non\-identity positioning matrix\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&18.\ \&Finding all Regions with RGB color 180 180 180\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch \-type region ( \-attr color=180/180/180 \-or \-attr rgb=180/180/180 ) \fR

      .PP
Prints all regions with their color attribute set to 180/180/180\&. Some files may use
\fIrgb\fR
instead of color, so to be comprehensive an
\fI\-or\fR
option is used to check both possibilities\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&19.\ \&Find All Combs Containing At Least One of Two Objects (dbfind)\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch |\&. ( \-depth 0 \-above=1 \-name obj1 ) \-or ( \-depth 0 \-above=1 \-name obj2 ) \fR

      .PP
Prints all combs immediately above either obj1 or obj2\&. This more or less mimics the results of the dbfind command, although it will be somewhat slower (noticably so on large databases\&.)

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&20.\ \&Finding all regions containing an intersection of obj2\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch |/ \-maxdepth 0 \-type region \-above ( \-name obj2 \-bool + ) \fR

      .PP
Prints all regions immediately above obj2 where obj2 is included using an intersection operation\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&21.\ \&Finding all Plate\-Mode BoT Objects\fR


      .PP
\fBsearch \-type bot \-param mode=plate \fR

      .PP
Prints all BoT primitives using "plate" mode, instead of the closed\-mesh\-requiring "volume" mode\&.

    

    
    .PP
\fBExample\ \&22.\ \&Verbose Reporting of Search Information\fR

      .PP
Search allows for multiple levels of verbose reporting\&. The first level will report the total number of items found\&. The second level will report the boolean operator used at each step along the path\&. The next, and final level, will report the primitive type of each object along the path\&. Increased verbosity can be supplied two different ways; as a single flag with each \*(Aqv\*(Aq indicating an elevated level (search \-vv\&.\&. ), as well as stacked \-v flags (search \-v \-v \&.\&.)\&.


      .PP
mged>\fBsearch \-v /all\&.g ! \-type comb\fR
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
/all\&.g/box\&.r/box\&.s
/all\&.g/cone\&.r/cone\&.s
/all\&.g/ellipse\&.r/ellipse\&.s
/all\&.g/light\&.r/LIGHT
/all\&.g/platform\&.r/platform\&.s
/all\&.g/tor\&.r/tor
[6] items found in search
	
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp


      .PP
First level of verbosity will print the total number of items found in the search\&. This is especially useful when coupled with the \*(Aq\-exec\*(Aq flag which may or may not print the number of items effected by the exec\&.


      .PP
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
mged> \fBsearch \-vv /all\&.g ! \-type comb\fR
    OR
mged> \fBsearch \-v \-v /all\&.g ! \-type comb\fR
	  
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp

.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
/u all\&.g/u box\&.r/u box\&.s
/u all\&.g/u cone\&.r/u cone\&.s
/u all\&.g/u ellipse\&.r/u ellipse\&.s
/u all\&.g/u light\&.r/u LIGHT
/u all\&.g/u platform\&.r/u platform\&.s
/u all\&.g/u tor\&.r/u tor
[6] items found in search
	
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp


      .PP
Second level of verbosity will print the total number of items found in the search as well as the boolean operators at each step along the path\&.


      .PP
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
mged> \fBsearch \-vvv /all\&.g ! \-type comb\fR
    OR
mged> \fBsearch \-v \-v \-v /all\&.g ! \-type comb\fR
	
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp

.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
/u all\&.g(c)/u platform\&.r(r)/u platform\&.s(arb8)
/u all\&.g(c)/u box\&.r(r)/u box\&.s(arb8)
/u all\&.g(c)/u cone\&.r(r)/u cone\&.s(tgc)
/u all\&.g(c)/u ellipse\&.r(r)/u ellipse\&.s(ell)
/u all\&.g(c)/u tor\&.r(r)/u tor(tor)
/u all\&.g(c)/u light\&.r(r)/u LIGHT(ell)
[6] items found in search
	
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp


      .PP
At max verbosity, print the total number of items found in the search, the boolean operators, and finally the primitive type of each object along the path\&.

    


    .PP
\fBExample\ \&23.\ \&Operating on Sets of search Results\fR

      .PP
There are two available methods for working with sets of
\fBsearch\fR
results\&. The first is the
\fBexec\fR
option, which is used in the following example to search for all regions below subtractions or intersections in the m35\&.g example model in BRL\-CAD and draw the objects\*(Aq wireframes in the display manager:
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
	  
	    mged> \fBsearch all\&.g \-type region \-and ( \-below \-bool \- \-or \-below \-bool + ) \-exec draw "{}" ";"\fR
	    mged> \fBautoview\fR
	  
	
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp


      .PP
Another possibility, especially useful for doing multiple sequential operations which would be awkward to write out in a single search line, is to assign the results of a search command to a Tcl variable\&. To illustrate, let\*(Aqs randomize the colors of all regions in the "cab" assembly of the m35\&.g example model and then assign a glass shader with transparency as a follow\-on step\&.

      .PP
First, we collect the set of search results into a Tcl variable:
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
	  
	    mged> \fB set glob_compat_mode 0\fR
	    mged> \fB set search_results [search cab \-type region]\fR
	  
	
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp


      .PP
Next we randomize the colors using Tcl\*(Aqs functionality (here we use random numbers and avoid any value less than 30 to keep objects more visible):
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
	  
	    mged> \fB foreach i $search_results {attr set $i color [expr {int(rand()*225)+30}]/[expr {int(rand()*225)+30}]/[expr {int(rand()*225)+30}]}\fR
	  
	
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp


      .PP
Finally, we add transparency to the same regions:
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
	  
	    mged> \fB foreach i $search_results {attr set $i shader {glass {tr 0\&.7 ri 1}}}\fR
	  
	
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp


      .if n \{\
.sp
.\}
.RS 4
.it 1 an-trap
.nr an-no-space-flag 1
.nr an-break-flag 1
.br
.ps +1
\fBNote\fR
.ps -1
.br

	.PP
Remember when setting region colors to check for the presence of a
\fIregionid_colortable\fR
attribute on the _GLOBAL object \- if such a table is present (the m35\&.g sample model has one, for example) you need to remove that table (and for MGED wireframes, re\-open the database) before the colors on the individual regions will "take":
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
	    
	      mged> \fB attr rm _GLOBAL regionid_colortable\fR
	    
	  
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp


      .sp .5v
.RE
    



  

